<TITLE>Governors budget fails disability workers</TITLE>


<TEXT>
As <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">noted</EVENT> in The Daily Gazettes article Local legislators weigh in on Cuomos state budget of <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="2017-01-19">January 19</TIMEX3> [p. A9], Gov. Andrew Cuomos budget reflects a rosy picture of middle class tax cuts, ride-sharing services and infrastructure spending. 
 
As the article states, however, there are apparent deficiencies. 
 
One in particular is that the budget clearly <EVENT eid="e2" class="I_STATE">fails</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">address</EVENT> the low wages of direct care workers  as noted by state Sen. George Amedore and Assemblyman Angelo Santabarbara  a position also <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">supported</EVENT> by other legislators from both sides of the aisle. 
 
These highly <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">dedicated</EVENT> critical care workers have enormous responsibility in caring for New York states physically and mentally disabled citizens, including our children. 
 
An <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">increase</EVENT> of $90 million would <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">provide</EVENT> important progress and would only be a tiny fraction of this over $150 billion budget  a small investment towards adequately compensating these grossly underpaid workers. 
Yet there is an absence of any <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">appreciation</EVENT> or <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">recognition</EVENT> of the most difficult and awesome responsibilities of these workers. 
 
They are responsible, and <EVENT eid="e10" class="STATE">culpable</EVENT> for, <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">dispensing</EVENT> life-sustaining medications multiple times throughout <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DURATION" value="PXD">the day</TIMEX3>, as well as <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE">supporting</EVENT> our children in meeting their essential daily needs. These needs include bathing, toileting, assistance with <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">dressing</EVENT>, cooking, feeding and <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">transporting</EVENT> our family members either to their jobs or day programs, where they receive speech and physical therapies. 
 
Why are these workers <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">forgotten</EVENT> once again? 
 
The article states already a vacancy rate of 10 percent and a turnover rate of over 20 percent. 
 
With all the attention and provision for increases for minimum wage and fast-food workers, the critical care worker is the forgotten step-child <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE" value="X">once</TIMEX3> again. 
 
It is completely predictable that those other wage increases will <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE">increase</EVENT> vacancies and turnover further and <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">jeopardize</EVENT> the care of our family membersthe most vulnerable in society. 
 
Clearly, significant budget provision is essential for these critical care workers who are grossly <EVENT eid="e18" class="STATE">underpaid</EVENT> for the incredible responsibilities they have. 
 
We <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">urge</EVENT> the governor and the legislators to <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">fulfill</EVENT> their most fundamental responsibilities to those who are unable to <EVENT eid="e21" class="OCCURRENCE">care</EVENT> for themselves and <EVENT eid="e22" class="OCCURRENCE">plug</EVENT> this most serious hole in New York states budget. 
 
New Yorks direct care worker wages must be substantially <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">increased</EVENT> so that the profession can <EVENT eid="e24" class="OCCURRENCE">attract</EVENT> and <EVENT eid="e25" class="OCCURRENCE">retain</EVENT> qualified employees to <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">preserve</EVENT> the public welfare. 
 
Surely there are many places to <EVENT eid="e27" class="OCCURRENCE">find</EVENT> this funding given this highest purpose of <EVENT eid="e28" class="OCCURRENCE">preserving</EVENT> the public welfare  the most fundamental and greatest obligation of our elected leaders. 
 
ENYDDA is an independent, all-volunteer organization <EVENT eid="e29" class="OCCURRENCE">founded</EVENT> in <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DATE" value="2015">2015</TIMEX3> to <EVENT eid="e30" class="OCCURRENCE">advocate</EVENT> for disabled family members and <EVENT eid="e31" class="OCCURRENCE">educate</EVENT> policymakers and the public on matters impacting the developmentally disabled. Christopher Corbett is a member of the organizations steering committee.
</TEXT>


